snippet.textDisplay:
I love how ironically every critic who loved "The Last Jedi" all are saying that they are upset that the film is tonally inconsistent with the previous film, which is what every major fan criticism of "The Last Jedi" was saying about that film. And it's funny, that they are upset that this film does to "The Last Jedi" what it did to "The Force Awakens" but when it was done in that film, it was provocative and brave and bold, but now it's fan service, and retreading. This guy complains of a lack of consistency with this film to it's predecessor, but that was what "The Last Jedi" was to all 7 films before it.

And the guy in this video is literally parroting every fanboy he trashed for bashing The Last Jedi, in trashing The Rise Of Skywalker. It's so funny to hear him say, "I wished they would have continued down the direction of The Last Jedi" which is the only thing any of the other fans of the 7 movies prior to that film was wishing that film would have done.

Look I saw the film. I didn't love it as much as I loved A New Hope, Empire Strikes Back, and The Force Awakens, but I didn't hate anything in the film either. Ultimately I would give the film 7/10. I feel it is the most "Star Wars" Star Wars Film Ever. If you could sum up ALL of the GOOD and ALL of the BAD of the entire 9 episodic saga, you will end up with this movie. If you have never seen any of the Star Wars movies then this film is literally everything about that story in one.

The Rise of Skywalker is a perfect example of what happens when the people in charge of one of the most impactful movie franchises on planet earth don't have a plan in place.

I didn't hate the film but I was beyond disappointed with the direction that JJ took. The plot moved at light speed and I just wanted to scream SLOW DOWN! at the screen throughout the whole film.

I won't get into spoilers here because people definitely need to see this knowing absolutely nothing of the plot. I did call several BIG reveals before it even came out though, maybe you will have called a few yourselves 🤔

Visually it's absolutely stunning and it definitely needs to be seen on the BIG screen 🤯

Being a big fan of The Last Jedi (minus the terrible canto bight section of the film), I was excited to see how JJ would expand upon the endless possibilities that Rian Johnson created but ultimately those possibilities were left in the dust for the most part.

In short, this movie wasn't for me and I was left feeling as if I was "force" fed an endless amount of fan service that left me feeling almost nothing at all.

To end on a positive note though, as I was walking out of the cinema there was a dad with his young son walking next to me and the kid was absolutely ecstatic about the film. He was rapid firing all of the big moments of the film at his dad with pure joy and that young fandom moment made me smile really wide.

Everyone will take something different away from this saga and of course it's not perfect but it's been one hell of a journey even if the landing didn't stick for me in the end.

Be your own critic of course and see where you land with this final installment 😉 and May The Force Be With You 💛

He says around 19:14 that TLJ was incongruous with TFA while RoS is a refutation of TLJ. 
Then, my problem is why applaud TLJ for its refutation from TFA while feeling numb towards RoS for its refutation of TLJ.

I did enjoy some parts of TLJ (including those he mentions like the light-speed attack and the Rey-Kylo team-up). And while RoS goes too far sometimes in the fan service and does feel like a re-thread of previous episodes of the original trilogy, I did enjoy it a lot, maybe moreso because it somewhat made the strange piece of the puzzle that TLJ is fit in the whole puzzle.

snippet.textDisplay: Just got back from The Rise of Skywalker.  I felt like it was One Third a terrible movie, One Third an Okay movie, and One Third a really good movie in that order.  I completely agree with Dan's assessment that the beginning comes out of absolutely no where and was set up by NOTHING that came before it in the previous films.  I didn't necessarily know what to expect when Dan and Roth mentioned a Russian Nesting Doll of Macguffins going into the film but I certainly get that comparison now because they literally are chasing thing after thing that is meant to lead to a thing.  The last third of the movie is genuinely very good, but it definitely cannot save how boring the first third is and how forced and cliched some of the things in the middle are.  Overall I definitely enjoyed a fair amount of it, but it is certainly far from what I would call a great movie which honestly just makes me sad.  I was hoping my opinion would differ from Dan's (like I did with The Greatest Showman) and Roth's but I feel very much like a mix between Roth and Dan at the moment.
